Install any official plugins which contains any tools with `create_link_message`. 2. Create workflow or chatflow and place the tools. 3. Try to invoke the tool which will return LINK type message. To easy to reproduce the issue, I've attached minimal tool here: [link_demo.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/21822961/link_demo.zip) (rename zip to difypkg to install) This is the minimal tool to reproduce: ```python from collections.abc import Generator from typing import Any from dify_plugin import Tool from dify_plugin.entities.tool import ToolInvokeMessage class LinkDemoTool(Tool): def _invoke(self, tool_parameters: dict[str, Any]) -> Generator[ToolInvokeMessage]: yield self.create_link_message("https://dify.ai/") ``` Affected official plugins are: ```bash $ grep -rE '^\s+yield self\.create_link_message' ./tools ./tools/hackernews/tools/get_story_info.py: yield self.create_link_message(story_url) ./tools/telegraph/tools/telegraph.py: yield self.create_link_message(ph_link) ./tools/spotify/tools/spotify_get_track.py: yield self.create_link_message(track_info["preview_url"]) ./tools/searchapi/tools/google.py: yield self.create_link_message(link=result) ./tools/searchapi/tools/google_jobs.py: yield self.create_link_message(link=result) ./tools/google_calendar/tools/create_event.py: yield self.create_link_message(created_event["htmlLink"]) ./tools/zoom/tools/zoom_update_meeting.py: yield self.create_link_message(updated_meeting["join_url"]) ./tools/zoom/tools/zoom_list_meetings.py: yield self.create_link_message(meeting["join_url"]) ./tools/zoom/tools/zoom_get_meeting.py: yield self.create_link_message(meeting_info["join_url"]) ./tools/zoom/tools/zoom_create_meeting.py: yield self.create_link_message(meeting_info["join_url"]) ./tools/wolframalpha/tools/wolframalpha.py: yield self.create_link_message(response_data["queryresult"]["sources"]["url"]) ./tools/twitter/tools/get_user_info.py: yield self.create_link_message(profile_url) ./tools/twitter/tools/send_tweet.py: yield self.create_link_message(f"https://twitter.com/user/status/{tweet_id}") ``` ### ‚úîÔ∏è Expected Behavior The link message has been returned. ### ‚ùå Actual Behavior ```bash Run failed: (psycopg2.errors.InvalidTextRepresentation) invalid input syntax for type uuid: "" LINE 3: WHERE tool_files.id = ''::UUID ^ [SQL: SELECT tool_files.id, tool_files.user_id, tool_files.tenant_id, tool_files.conversation_id, tool_files.file_key, tool_files.mimetype, tool_files.original_url, tool_files.name, tool_files.size FROM tool_files WHERE tool_files.id = %(id_1)s::UUID] [parameters: {'id_1': ''}] (Background on this error at: https://sqlalche.me/e/20/9h9h) ```

pull_request.title: Multiple scoped HRQs with the same name
pull_request.body:
Previously, there was an issue where the names of scoped RQs created from scoped HRQs could conflict. This PR fixes that problem.

# Problem

In the previous implementation, the name of a scoped RQ was just a prefixed version of the scoped HRQ name. As a result, if a parent namespace and a child namespace had scoped HRQs with the same name, it would try to create RQs with the same name in the child namespace and fail.

# Solution

This PR changes the RQ naming to include the namespace name and an MD5 hash of `hrqNamespace/hrqName`. However, since this can make the name exceed the length limit, the name is truncated appropriately when it's too long.

issue.title: Add auto-fillet for R.2.1 (code available)
issue.body:
As per [R2.1 ‚Äî Use chamfers on edges parallel to the print surface. Use fillets on edges vertical to the print surface](https://blog.rahix.de/design-for-3d-printing/#rule-R2.), it's nice to add fillets non-horizontal edges to reduce the acceleration and improve accuracy.

However I found this to be quite tedious, especially since it's best applied as a last step in the design, for ordering of operations, requires selecting a very large number of edges, and has to be re-done if updating the underlying design because edge references may change.
So I made a macro for it.
I was wondering if perhaps you'd want to add it in here, accessible at the click of a button, and with customizable parameters (such as fillet radius).

Please feel free to use the following:
<details>
<summary>
Code
</summary>

```python
import FreeCAD as App
import FreeCADGui as Gui

doc = App.ActiveDocument
if doc is None:
    raise RuntimeError("No active document")

# -- Get the active PartDesign Body, with a simple fallback --
body = None
view = Gui.activeView()
if view:
    body = view.getActiveObject("pdbody")
if not body:
    # fallback: use the single body in the doc if exactly one exists
    bodies = [o for o in doc.Objects if o.TypeId == "PartDesign::Body"]
    if len(bodies) == 1:
        body = bodies[0]
if not body:
    raise RuntimeError("No active PartDesign Body found")

# Get the tip of the body
tip = body.Tip
if tip is None:
    raise RuntimeError("Body has no Tip")

shape = tip.Shape
edges = shape.Edges

filtered = []
for idx, edge in enumerate(edges, start=1):
    param = edge.ParameterRange
    mid = 0.5 * (param[0] + param[1])
    tangent = edge.tangentAt(mid)
    if abs(tangent.z) > 1e-6:
        filtered.append("Edge{}".format(idx))

if not filtered:
    raise RuntimeError("No edges with Z component found")

body = tip.getParentGeoFeatureGroup()

if not body or body.TypeId != "PartDesign::Body":
    raise RuntimeError("Could not find main body")

# Create a PartDesign Fillet inside the same body
fillet = body.newObject("PartDesign::Fillet", "Round for manufacturing")
fillet.Base = (tip, filtered)
fillet.Radius = 1.0

body.Tip = fillet

doc.recompute()
```
</details>

(I just want to raise the warning that this might miss some edges if they start and end at the same z but actually go through different z values)

comment.body:
Interesting idea!  I never considered automating this, because in my design workflow, this macro mostly would not work.  There are a few reasons:

1. I don't design in the "print space" but rather using a coordinate system logical to the function of the part.  Mostly orienting the part similar to its orientation when installed later.  So the Z axis is quite often not actually the printer's Z.  This could be fixed by adding a dialog to the command where the user selects the print orientation.
2. It's not just vertical edges that get fillets, but basically every edge up to 45¬∞.  This should also be trivial to fix.
2. In most of my designs, I have to apply fillets quite early to make the CAD kernel happy.  FreeCAD (more correctly OCCT) often fails to make fillets of edges which join into complicated geometry, so thought has to be put into where fillets can actually work and at what stage of the design they should be added.
3. From a design perspective, I choose the sizes of each fillet with a lot of intent.  There are often functional constraints to the size of a fillet that can be added.  On the other hand, fillets should be as big as possible for the best printability.

That all said, I could imagine such a one-click "create fillets along a selected axis" command could be useful for a some very simple and fast designs.  The generated fillet feature can also be edited later, so it can serve as a basis for future work.

Maybe some other people can comment on their thoughts?  If there is some interest, I'd be willing to integrate this!

commits.message:
Fix mute button and toast message synchronization issues

This commit fixes several bugs related to the mute functionality and refactors the code for better state management.

1.  **Android TV**: The in-app mute button required two presses to unmute. This was caused by the app and the system both trying to handle the mute event. The fix is to have the in-app button use the `AudioManager` to toggle the system mute state, which the app then reacts to.

2.  **Mobile**: Using the hardware volume buttons to unmute the app would not update the in-app mute button's state.

3.  **Toast Messages**: Toasts for mute/unmute were not showing up when the in-app button was pressed.

To fix these issues, the mute state management has been centralized and improved in the `MediaPlaybackService`.

- A `MuteStateListener` interface has been introduced to allow the `MainActivity` and `TvActivity` to observe the mute state from the service and update their UIs accordingly.
- The `VolumeChangeReceiver` has been improved to robustly detect the system's mute state by checking both `isStreamMute()` and the volume level.
- The `onClickListener` for the in-app mute button in both activities now uses `AudioManager.ADJUST_TOGGLE_MUTE` to delegate the mute action to the system, preventing race conditions.
- The context for displaying `Toast` notifications has been changed to the application context to prevent `BadTokenException` errors.
- The `FLAG_SHOW_UI` flag was removed from the `adjustStreamVolume` call to prevent the system's volume slider from appearing on mobile.

Changelog:

The validate-iri library hangs indefinitely on URLs with invalid percent-encoding like %prettyVersion% where %pr is not a valid hex sequence. This fix detects such malformed sequences early and also replaces known placeholders with actual version strings.

Fixes issue with packages from Codeberg that use URL placeholders.
